When [[Kingdom of Italy|Italy]] declared war on Austria-Hungary in May 1915, five incomplete F-group boats were towed to be completed in safety. ''82 F'', ''83 F'' and ''84 F'' were taken from Porto Re to [[Pula|Pola]], and ''90 F'' and ''91 F'' were taken to [[Novigrad, Zadar County|Novigrad]]. This resulted in delays to the completion of these boats.{{sfn|Greger|1976|p=60}}

===M-group===
[[File:Austro-Hungarian torpedo boat 98 M.jpg|thumb|300px|First of the "M"-group, ''98 M'', underway|alt=black and white photograph of a vessel underway]]
The M-group were built by CNT at [[Monfalcone]] between March 1914 and March 1916. They had a waterline length of {{convert|60.5|m|ftin|abbr=on}}, a beam of {{convert|5.6|m|ftin|abbr=on}}, and a normal draught of {{convert|1.5|m|ftin|abbr=on}}. While their designed displacement was {{convert|270|t|LT|0}}, they displaced about {{convert|330|t|LT}} fully loaded. The crew consisted of 38 officers and enlisted men. Their Melms-Pfenniger turbines were rated at {{convert|5000|shp|lk=no|abbr=on}} with a maximum output of {{convert|6000|shp|lk=no|abbr=on}}, and the boats were designed to reach a top speed of {{convert|28.5|kn}}. They carried enough coal and fuel oil to give them a range of {{convert|1200|nmi|lk=no|abbr=on}} at {{convert|16|kn}}.{{sfn|Greger|1976|p=63}}

