===World War II===
By 1940, thirteen boats of the class had been lost or scrapped, including all six Portuguese boats.{{sfn|Greger|1976|pp=58, 60 & 63}} At the time of the [[Axis powers|Axis]] [[invasion of Yugoslavia]] in April 1941, the Yugoslav boats ''T1'' and ''T3'' were assigned to the Southern Sector of Coastal Defence Command based at the Bay of Kotor, along with several [[minesweeper]]s and other craft.{{sfn|Niehorster|2013a}} ''T5''–''T8'' comprised the 3rd Torpedo Division located at [[Šibenik]].{{sfn|Niehorster|2013b}} On 8 April, the four boats of the 3rd Torpedo Division, along with other vessels, were tasked to support an attack on the Italian enclave of [[Zadar]] on the Dalmatia coast. They were subjected to three Italian air attacks and, after the last one, sailed from the area of [[Zaton, Zadar County|Zaton]] into [[Lake Prokljan]], where they remained until 11 April.{{sfn|Terzić|1982|p=333}} On 12 April, the 3rd Torpedo Division arrived at [[Milna]] on the island of [[Brač]], and refused to follow orders to sail to the Bay of Kotor.{{sfn|Terzić|1982|p=404}} All six Yugoslav boats were then captured by the Italians.{{sfn|Greger|1976|pp=58 & 60}}

The five surviving Greek boats were all sunk by aircraft during the [[Battle of Greece|German invasion of Greece]], also in April 1941. The first was ''Proussa'', which was sunk off Corfu on 4 April by Italian [[Junkers Ju 87]] "Picchiatello"s of the 239th Squadron, 97th Dive Bomber Group.{{sfn|Weal|1998|p=22}}{{refn|According to Greger, ''Proussa'' was sunk by German bombers on the same day and at the same location.{{sfn|Greger|1976|p=63}}|group = lower-alpha}} Later, ''Kios'' was sunk off [[Athens]] on 22 April, ''Kyzikos'' at [[Salamis Naval Base|Salamis]] on 24 April, ''Pergamos'' off Salamis on 25 April, and ''Kydoniai'' south of the [[Peloponnese]] peninsula on the following day, all by German aircraft.{{sfn|Greger|1976|p=63}}

The three Romanian boats were initially deployed against the [[Soviet Navy]] [[Black Sea Fleet]] following the launch of [[Operation Barbarossa]] in June 1941,{{sfn|Greger|1976|pp=58, 60 & 63}} with ''Naluca'' and ''Sborul'' allocated to the 3rd Section of the [[Romanian Naval Forces|Romanian Navy]]. On 9 July 1941, ''Naluca'', along with a [[gunboat]] and three [[Motor Torpedo Boat]]s (MTBs), sank the Soviet submarine ''SC-206'' off the southern Romanian coast near [[Mangalia]].{{sfn|Smillie|2012|p=134}} Between 7–16 October 1941, all three Romanian torpedo boats were part of the escort for a minelaying group that laid several minefields along the Bulgarian coast to protect Axis shipping.{{sfn|Smillie|2012|p=324}} ''Naluca'' was sunk by Soviet aircraft at [[Constanța]] on 20 August 1944, but ''Sborul'' and ''Smeul'' survived World War II,{{sfn|Greger|1976|pp=58 & 60}} having been transferred to the Soviet Black Sea Fleet in late August 1944 after Romania changed sides and joined the Allies, serving as ''Musson'' and ''Toros'' respectively.{{sfn|Monakov|Rohwer|2001|pp=167 & 171}}

The Yugoslav boats served in a coastal and second-line escort role with the [[Regia Marina|Royal Italian Navy]] ({{lang-it|Regia Marina}}) in the Adriatic under their Yugoslav designations, and were fitted with two {{convert|76|mm|in|abbr=on}} L/30 anti-aircraft guns in place of their {{convert|66|mm|in|abbr=on}} guns,{{sfn|Brescia|2012|p=151}} but no other significant alterations were made to them.{{sfn|Chesneau|1980|p=304}} After the Italians [[Armistice of Cassibile|capitulated]] in September 1943, they transferred ''T1'' back to the KJRM-in-exile in December of that year.{{refn|group=lower-alpha|One source states that she was captured by the Germans and transferred to the [[Navy of the Independent State of Croatia|navy]] of the puppet state, the [[Independent State of Croatia]],{{sfn|Gardiner|1985|p=339}} but several other sources state that she was returned to the KJRM in December 1943.{{sfn|Brescia|2012|p=151}}{{sfn|Chesneau|1980|p=357}}{{sfn|Whitley|1988|p=186}}}} ''T3'' was seized by the Germans at Rijeka on 16 September 1943 and was renamed ''TA48''. She was commissioned on 15 August 1944, and was used for patrol and escort work in the northern Adriatic.{{sfn|Whitley|1988|p=81}} The Germans added to her armament, fitting her with two single {{convert|20|mm|in|abbr=on}} anti-aircraft guns in addition to the guns fitted by the Italians, and removing two of her torpedo tubes.{{sfn|Lenton|1975|p=107}} She was either crewed exclusively by Croatian officers and sailors but remained under German control,{{sfn|Gardiner|1985|p=339}} or was transferred to the Croatian navy but then repossessed by the Germans on 14 December 1944 due to the unreliable nature of the Croatian navy.{{sfn|Whitley|1988|p=81}} Her complement was also increased to 52 during her German/Croatian service.{{sfn|Gardiner|1985|p=339}} She was sunk in the port of Trieste by [[Allies of World War II|Allied]] aircraft on 20 February 1945.{{sfn|Gardiner|1985|p=339}}{{sfn|Chesneau|1980|p=357}}{{refn|Sources conflict on who sank ''TA48''. Gardiner and Lenton state that they were Allied aircraft without specifying their nationality,{{sfn|Gardiner|1985|p=339}}{{sfn|Lenton|1975|p=110}} while Chesneau states they were British aircraft,{{sfn|Chesneau|1980|p=357}} and Wilmott states that US aircraft carried out the attack.{{sfn|Willmott|2010|p=209}}|group = lower-alpha}}

''T5'' was also returned to the KJRM-in-exile in December 1943.{{sfn|Gardiner|1985|p=339}} ''T6'' was scuttled by the Italians {{convert|30|km|abbr=on}} north of [[Rimini]] on 11 September as she had insufficient fuel on board to reach an Allied port.{{sfn|Brown|1995|p=92}} Once under German control, ''T7'' was also handed over to the Navy of the Independent State of Croatia, and served under her Yugoslav designation. Her crew came under the influence of the [[Yugoslav Partisans]], and were preparing to mutiny when the Germans intervened.{{sfn|Gardiner|1985|p=339}}{{sfn|Chesneau|1980|p=357}} On 24 June 1944, she and the [[E-boat|S-boats]] ''S 154'' and ''S 157'' of the 7th S-Boat Flotilla were sailing between [[Šibenik]] and [[Rijeka]], protecting German sea supply routes along the Adriatic when they were attacked by the [[Royal Navy]] [[Fairmile D motor torpedo boat]]s ''MTB 659'', ''MTB 662'' and ''MTB 670'' near the island of Kukuljari, south of [[Murter|Murter Island]]. The MTBs fired two torpedoes at ''T7'', but missed, so they closed and engaged her with their guns, setting her ablaze. She was beached, and 21 crew were rescued by the MTBs. The British crews later examined the wreck, capturing five more crew, then destroyed her with demolition charges.{{sfn|Paterson|2015|p=223}} ''T8'' was sunk {{convert|37|km|abbr=on}} north-west of [[Dubrovnik]] by German aircraft while evacuating Italian troops from Dalmatia on 10 or 11 September 1943.{{sfn|Gardiner|1985|p=339}}{{sfn|Chesneau|1980|p=357}}{{sfn|Whitley|1988|p=186}}{{sfn|Brown|1995|p=92}}

===Post-World War II===
Only four of the twenty-seven 250t-class torpedo boats survived World War II, two in Yugoslav service and two in Soviet service. ''T1'' was commissioned by the [[Yugoslav Navy]] after the war as ''Golešnica''.{{sfn|Chesneau|1980|p=357}} She was re-armed with two {{convert|40|mm|in|abbr=on}} guns on single mounts and four {{convert|20|mm|in|abbr=on}} guns, and her torpedo tubes were removed. She continued in Yugoslav service under that name until October 1959. ''T5'' was also commissioned by the Yugoslav Navy after the war,{{sfn|Chesneau|1980|p=357}} and renamed ''Cer''. She was fitted with two {{convert|40|mm|in|abbr=on}} guns on single mounts and one {{convert|20|mm|in|abbr=on}} gun, and her torpedo tubes were also removed. She served until 1962, when she was broken up.{{sfn|Gardiner|1983|p=388}} ''Musson'' and ''Toros'' were returned to Romania in October 1945, and stricken the following month.{{sfn|Monakov|Rohwer|2001|p=270}}{{refn|According to Greger, ''Toros'' survived the war and was scrapped in 1960.{{sfn|Greger|1976|p=60}}|group = lower-alpha}}

